    <body>
        <p>Lets you use the default look for objects in <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture">an image</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Mimic">a frame</MadCap:conditionalText>. In other words, you can remove the formatting from the selected object(s) and apply the default formatting for that particular type of object (e.g., oval, rectangle, bubble, line). For example, let's say you are drawing a rectangle on <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture">an image</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Mimic">a frame</MadCap:conditionalText>. When you select the rectangle tool from the local toolbar, the default factory settings are such that the rectangle initially has a thin black border and no fill color. You can apply, say, a green fill color to that object. If you then decide that you want to return to the default setting (in this case, no fill color), you can select this option. <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Capture">See <MadCap:xref href="../../../Appearance/Look_of_Objects/Using_the_Default_Look_for_Objects_Capture.htm" target="" title="" alt="">Using the Default Look for Objects</MadCap:xref>.</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="Products.Mimic">See <MadCap:xref href="../../../Appearance/Look_of_Objects/Using_the_Default_Look_for_Objects_Mimic.htm">Using the Default Look for Objects</MadCap:xref>.</MadCap:conditionalText></p>
    </body>
</html>